        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <div type="transcription">
                    
<p rend="left">in hand, the first time I can see him I will find out all particulars &amp; let you know. “Blushing” commences quite as early as 5 y<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. as I have two fine little Blushers of this age on show at Chesham School.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Believe me | Yours very truly | Stephen P Engleheart</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="annotations">
                <note>1.1 in hand, … know.] <hi rend="italic">crossed red crayon</hi></note>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date is established by the fact that Engleheart, the Down surgeon, left Down in or before October 1869 (<hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 17, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6942.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. B. Innes, 18 October 1869</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Presumably Engleheart refers to the infant school in Chesham, Buckinghamshire. He is not recorded as resident in Buckinghamshire in <hi rend="italic">Medical directory</hi>, the <hi rend="italic">Post Office directory of Northamptonshire etc.</hi>, or the national censuses. CD discussed the age at which blushing began in <hi rend="italic">Expression</hi>, p. 311.</note>
        </div>        
            
